  "The process of a compound splitting into ions in water": "",
  "The process of evaporating water from a solution": "",
  "The process of freezing a liquid into a solid state": "",
  "Dissociation is the process of a compound separating into its ions when dissolved in water. For acids, this means releasing H⁺ ions; for bases, it means releasing OH⁻ ions.": "",
  "A student dissolves NH₃ (ammonia) in water. It does not contain OH⁻ in its formula, but the solution tests as basic. Which definition best explains why NH₃ is a base?": "",
  "Arrhenius, because NH₃ releases OH⁻ directly from its formula": "",
  "Bronsted-Lowry, because NH₃ accepts a proton (H⁺) from water": "",
  "Neither definition can explain why NH₃ is a base": "",
  "Arrhenius, because all nitrogen compounds are bases": "",
  "NH₃ does not contain OH⁻, so Arrhenius cannot easily explain it as a base. However, NH₃ accepts a proton from water (NH₃ + H₂O -> NH₄⁺ + OH⁻), making it a Bronsted-Lowry base.": "",
